column12: Bookmark Video presents a Moving Images Production. [Manila] : Bookmark Video, 1998. (43 min.)

column24: Viva Films. Diliman, Quezon City : Viva Video, c1999.
column25: The tragic, yet true story of a Flor Contemplacion, a Filipina domestic helper who was falsely accused of murder in Singapore -- a falsehood she could not have committed. Her futile struggle for justice and freedom exposes the current realities facing ordinary Overseas Contract Workers -- victims of injustice in nations like Singapore and the United Arab Emirates.
column29: Neo Films, Johns Hopkins University ; an Antonio Jose Perez film ; written by Amado L. Lacuesta, Jr., Antonio Jose Perez ; produced by Eric M. Cuatico ; executive producer, Patrick L. Coleman ; executive producer, Vic del Rosario, Jr. ; directed by Antonio Jose Perez.
column30: Joseph is a young doctor who returned to his hometown in the Mountain Province to bury his father, an Ifugao chieftain, who was killed during a tribal dispute. While there, he discovers his rich heritage and acquires pride in his being an Ifugao. Though the lure of a career in America remains strong, he is unable to resist the urge to help his village, which has resisted modern medicine and is now in the midst of a pneumonia epidemic and a civil war.
column34: Viva Films ; story & screenplay, Mike Vergara ; produced by Ramon Salvador ; executive producer, Vic del Rosario, Jr. ; directed by Danny Zialcita. Diliman, Quezon City : Viva Video, c2001.
column35: Relationships and inter-relationships, couples and couplings provide a dramatic medium for the unfolding of a town's so-called "honorable" citizens. The story takes a twist when blackmail comes into the picture and murder rears its ugly head. This sets into motion the unraveling of more skeletons in the closet and an expose of the intricate complexities of life and people.
column39: Tangent Films International ; a film by Mel Chionglo ; story and screenplay by Ricardo Lee ; executive producer, Richard Tang. Diliman, Quezon City : Viva Video, c1999.
column40: Three young good-looking brothers live with and support their parents in Manila where they dance at the male Club Exotica and work as "call boys." Joel has a wife and child; he and Dennis are saving money to buy back lost family land. Sonny has dropped out of university and sees dancing as a way to make money for now. Joel has a regular boyfriend as well; Sonny spends time with Michelle, a transvestite; Dennis and his pals steal car radios. When their nanay takes in a homeless youth who is not what he appears to be, a chain of events is set in motion that brings tragedy.
column44: Millenium Cinema ; story, Raymond Burgos ; screenplay, Willy Laconsay ; producer, Eric M. Cuatico. Diliman, Quezon City : Viva Video, c2001.
column45: Based on true events tells of how Police General Panfilo Lacson rose from the ranks after his graduation from the Philippine Military Academy in 1971. Featuring Ping's battle against kidnappers, car thieves and other organized crime, this film includes highlights of Gen. Lacson's career such as the rescue of Robina Gokongwei, the capture of the Light A Fire Movement, his participation during the EDSA revolution and his controversial stint as head of Task Force Habagat of the Presidential Anti-Crime Commission.
column49: Viva Films ; story research & screenplay, Amado Lacuesta, Francis "Jun" Posadas ; produced by William C. Leary ; executive producer, Vic del Rosario, Jr. ; directed by Francis "Jun" Posadas. Diliman, Quezon City : Viva Video, c2001.
column50: Based on true events tells the story of Max Asuncion, the most celebrated and controversial judge ever to hit the headlines in the Philippines. Be a witness to the man behind the most sensational court cases in Philippine history and why he earned the monicker "the Hanging Judge."
column54: Viva Films ; based on the novel by Domingo Landicho ; screenplay, Ricky Lee ; producers, Vicente G. del Rosario III, Veronique del Rosario-Corpus ; executive producer, Vic del Rosario, Jr. ; directed by Joel C. Lamangan. Diliman, Quezon City : Viva Video, c2000.
column55: The daughter of impoverished parents, Ada's life becomes even more miserable when her father is imprisoned after attempting to rob a bank. For them to survive Ada's mother, Azun, gives in to Timo's offer that they live with him. A heartless usurer, Timo rapes Ada. Azun turns a deaf ear to Ada's complaint, and she instead accuses her of being an ingrate. Forsaken by her own mother, Ada leaves home and becomes a sexy dancer to survive.
column59: A GMA Films production ; a Joel C. Lamangan film ; story, Ricardo A. Lee, Butch Jimenez and Joel C. Lamangan ; screenplay, Ricardo A. Lee and Manny Q. Palo ; produced by Butch Jimenez and Jimmy Duavit ; executive producer, Menardo R. Jimenez, Gilberto M. Duavit, Felipe L. Gozon ; directed by Joel C. Lamangan. Diliman, Quezon City : Viva Video, c2001.
column60: Sonny lived a miserable life in the Manila slums, but it was nothing compared to prison. Nevertheless, it's in prison where Sonny encounters someone who is a true friend.
column64: A GMA Films production of a Marilou Diaz-Abaya film ; screenplay, Ricardo Lee, Jun Lana ; produced by Butch Jimenez, Jimmy Duavit, Marilou Diaz-Abaya ; executive producers, Menardo R. Jimenez, Gilberto M. Duavit, Felipe L. Gozon ; directed by Marilou Diaz-Abaya. Diliman, Quezon City : Viva Video, c2001.
column65: A greedy fishing captain hires child laborers to use the hazardous muro-ami method of pounding coral to scare the fish and drive them into nets. Disregarding his father's advice about not abusing the abundance of the sea, he must face its wrath.
column69: Direksiyon at kamera, Fruto Corre. [Manila] : Bookmark Video, 2000.
